Imagine a very long web page with many sections (e.g., specifications on a single HTML page). If a user requests a specific section (e.g., page.html#section7), what would happen if the web server streamed this section first, then the others?
Order of the stream:
1. beginning of the HTML document up to <body>
2. HTML for section 7
3. HTML for sections 1, 2, 3, etc.
The browser would then ensure that sections 1 to 6 are inserted *above* section 7 on the web page.
Does that make sense to you? Could it be useful?
What I want to achieve is for the rendering of the linked section (#section7) to be as fast as possible without having to reimplement anything with JavaScript. I just want to have a very long HTML document, but with the rendering of the linked sections as fast as possible. This should work with HTML alone.
The content could be streamed in this way, and then the browser would inject each <contents> into its <div>.
<div id=sec1></div>
<div id=sec2></div>
etc.
<div id=sec7>section 7…</div>
<contents for=sec1>section 1…</contents>
<contents for=sec2>section 2…</contents>
etc.
It would be streamed in a disorderly fashion, but the browser would assemble the HTML document as if it were streamed in order.
@user22 You can reorganize the documents like this even without JS. You cannot use the hash part of the URL if you want the server to do something, but you can use query string parameters to tell the server which section you want to see first. To reorganize the parts, you have the choice between:
1. Using cascading style sheets
2. Using a template with placeholders
@user23 Yes. The problem is that the visual order (what the user sees) does not match the DOM order. It could be useful to have an HTML feature that allows streaming out of order, and then the browser would rearrange the content in the DOM in the correct order.
But the approach using positions seems promising. I'll try it.
@user22 Oh, you want the browser to fix the DOM order?
@user23 Yes, that's the idea. Section 7 would be streamed first so that the user can see it as soon as possible. It would be great if it could do this without affecting the DOM order, so that the browser can ensure that the final DOM order matches the visual order.
In other words, stream section 7 first, but make sure the final result (DOM and visual) is as if all sections had been streamed in order.
@user22 @user23 Check out PHOOOS without JS: https://github.com/niutech/phooos
